## Historical and Legal Context in the United States

Martial law has been declared in the United States on limited occasions, often in response to war, insurrection, natural disasters, or civil unrest ([Wikipedia, 2023](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Martial_law_in_the_United_States)).

| Event/Period                | Reason for Martial Law Declaration                  | Scope/Duration                 |
|----------------------------|----------------------------------------------------|-------------------------------|
| Civil War (1863)            | Rebellion and invasion                              | National level, suspension of habeas corpus |
| Great Chicago Fire (1871)   | Natural disaster                                   | Localized, temporary           |
| San Francisco Earthquake (1906) | Natural disaster                               | Localized, temporary           |
| Pearl Harbor (1941)         | War and invasion                                   | Hawaii, multi-year             |
| Civil Rights Movement (1960s) | Civil unrest and riots                           | Localized, temporary           |

The **Posse Comitatus Act (1878)** limits the military's role in domestic law enforcement, requiring congressional approval for military involvement in civilian policing ([Wikipedia, 2023](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Martial_law_in_the_United_States)).

